<h2>Dosing by Total Testosterone Response</h2>

<ul style="margin: 24px 0;">
  <li><strong>If T increases to 500-800 ng/dL on 12.5mg:</strong> Stay at 12.5mg (sweet spot)</li>
  <li><strong>If T under 500 ng/dL on 12.5mg:</strong> Increase to 25mg 2x/week</li>
  <li><strong>If T above 900 ng/dL:</strong> Reduce to 12.5mg once weekly or 6.25mg 2x/week</li>
</ul>

<h2>Daily vs Twice Weekly Dosing</h2>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Protocol</th><th>Pros</th><th>Cons</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>12.5mg 2x/week</strong></td><td>Easier compliance, stable levels, lower side effects</td><td>May have mild fluctuation</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>6.25mg daily</strong></td><td>Most stable levels, mimics natural rhythm</td><td>Must remember daily</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> Start with 12.5mg twice weekly (Monday/Thursday). Most men get excellent results with fewer side effects than daily dosing.</p>

<h2>Timeline: What to Expect</h2>

<ul style="margin: 24px 0;">
  <li><strong>Week 1-2:</strong> Minimal changes (LH/FSH starting to rise)</li>
  <li><strong>Week 2-4:</strong> Early T increase (200-300 ng/dL boost), energy improves</li>
  <li><strong>Week 4-8:</strong> Peak T levels reached (300-500 ng/dL boost), symptom relief</li>
  <li><strong>Week 8-12:</strong> Stabilization, continued benefits</li>
</ul>

<h2>Lab Monitoring Schedule</h2>

<ol style="margin: 24px 0;">
  <li><strong>Baseline:</strong> Total T, Free T, LH, FSH, Estradiol, CBC, CMP</li>
  <li><strong>Week 8:</strong> Total T, LH, FSH, Estradiol (adjust dose if needed)</li>
  <li><strong>Week 16:</strong> Full panel + semen analysis (if fertility important)</li>
  <li><strong>Every 6 months:</strong> Total T, Free T, Estradiol, CBC, CMP</li>
</ol>

<h2>Side Effects by Dose</h2>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Side Effect</th><th>12.5mg</th><th>25mg</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Vision changes</strong></td><td>Rare (under 3%)</td><td>5-7%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Mood swings</strong></td><td>5-10%</td><td>15-20%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Gyno risk</strong></td><td>Low (3-5%)</td><td>Moderate (8-12%)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Headaches</strong></td><td>5%</td><td>10-15%</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Strategy:</strong> Start at 12.5mg to minimize side effects. Only increase to 25mg if testosterone response is inadequate (under 500 ng/dL).</p>

<h2>When to Adjust Dose</h2>

<p><strong>Increase dose (12.5mg → 25mg) if:</strong></p>
<ul style="margin: 24px 0;">
  <li>Total T still under 500 ng/dL after 8 weeks</li>
  <li>Symptoms not improving (low energy, libido)</li>
  <li>LH/FSH increased but T didn't respond adequately</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Decrease dose if:</strong></p>
<ul style="margin: 24px 0;">
  <li>Total T above 900 ng/dL (supraphysiological)</li>
  <li>Estradiol climbing above 50 pg/mL (gyno risk)</li>
  <li>Side effects (vision, mood) become problematic</li>
</ul>

